text.Taxonomy and naming:
Boronia inflexa was first formally described in 2003 by Marco F. Duretto and the description was published in the journal Muelleria from a specimen collected in the Girraween National Park. The specific epithet (inflexa) is a Latin word referring to the edges of the sepals, near their tip.In the same paper, Duretto described four new subspecies:
Boronia inflexa subsp. inflexa that has its branches and leaves covered with minute, soft hairs, and petals 2–3.5 mm (0.079–0.14 in) long;
Boronia inflexa subsp. montiazura that is glabrous with the end leaflet 3–7 mm (0.12–0.28 in) long and 0.5–1 mm (0.020–0.039 in) wide;
Boronia inflexa subsp. grandiflora that has its branches and leaves covered with minute, soft hairs, and petals 6.5–7 mm (0.26–0.28 in) long;
Boronia inflexa subsp. torringtonensis that is glabrous with the end leaflet 10–16 mm (0.39–0.63 in) long and 1–1.5 mm (0.039–0.059 in) wide.
